text: Surprisingly, I'm in love with the new version of the song.  It sounds amazing. Sadly, that is literally the only thing this trailer made me excited for. Lumiere's "French" accent makes me wince, the special effects look dodgy, I love the clock, but the tea set looks like something out of a low budget children's cartoon, I'm thus far unimpressed with Belle, I see none of her fire, wit or passion from the original Disney film. I like that the Beast has a little humour but I'm worried it will take away from his solemnity. Gaston is a huge disappointment, he's a beefcake for a reason, and the live action version gets a scrawny kid with too much gel in his hair, what happened to "roughly the size of a barge?".

text: People are bitching about this being a cash grab and nothing new being added and to the story, and to those people, I say: First, Hollywood is a business. Big film studios will make movies that are commercially viable first and foremost. If people pay to see them, they really don't care what the critics and moviegoers have to say about it. Why else would Warner Brothers keep making DC movies? Why else would Pixar make yet another Cars movie? Why else would they keep chugging out Star Wars movies, or multiple Marvel movies every year? God knows the blockbuster market is crowded as hell, but the ticket sales make it worth it. Secondly, they're adding three new songs, a new character, and new backstories for both Belle and the Beast. This movie is supposedly going to be 30-40 minutes longer than the original animated film. They have to make enough change so that it seems slightly different, but not too different to the point where the story is unrecognizable. Also, none of you have seen the finished film, so give it the benefit of the doubt. I'm optimistic. I see a few new things in this trailer that I'm excited about. So bitch and moan all you want, but Disney will keep making these until one flops.

text: Why do trailers keep showing the whole movie nowadays? I get it, we've all seen the original yadda yadda, but there's still magic in seeing just a couple of seconds of the movie. For example if we'd seen just until Belle meets the Beasts, I'm sure that'd be enough for people to get excited and see it or when she meets everyone in the castle. Besides people are forgetting that there are newer generations of children who have probably never seen the original or simply haven't grown with Disney classics. You want a fantastic trailer that shows and tells just enough to reel you in but not spoil the whole movie? Watch American Pastoral the trailer. That aside, this trailer was the first one of the bunch that actually made me excited for Beauty and the Beast oddly enough. Cuddos to you, Disney!

text: ok I am not saying that Ariana Grande and John legend are not good singers. I love John legend's songs and honestly as I am an Indian I don't even know the man who sang it in the older version. I know the woman was Celine Dion. It's just that in the older version the lines 'Barely even friends then somebody bends unexpectedly' are sung beautifully, not just that one line but every word completely captures the moment and meaning of their relationship. That feeling is lost in the persuit of making the song sound larger and dramatic. The song's beauty was it's clarity, that it had few instruments yet it felt big. Maybe it's just for trailer but God I hope I can listen to those words clearly and not just the instruments.

text: it pains me to see they didn't go the practical effects route, or atleast a little more hybrid with cg. Really they could have SO easily (but yeah expensively) hired one of those insane effects teams for this kind of anthropomorphic look, have the dude on stilts in a costume with a wellmade latex/sillicone mold on his face and some fur and it would have looked so much better. They could have done it even beastlier, just a glance at the effects in el laberintho del Fauno and Hellboy proves it, or I don't know, the whole Rick Baker legacy. Even parts of action scenes could be amazing with a stunt double on stilts. Don't know with actual wolves but still. Anyway, parts are not too bad, I like gaston and his mirror and his lovely flowers. And Kevin Kline seems awesome, but even simple shots like the one were she comes out of the house scream Lazy Town to me (gaston is their robbie rotten lol). So fake, I wonder if she actually holds that door. I think she does, but it's just the extremely obvious and somewhat senseless compositing....

text: Wonderful final trailer, and the music is absolutely epic (both the underscore and Ariana Grande & John Legend's rendition of the classic "Beauty and the Beast" title song). We honestly don't need to see anymore at this point as it would spoil the entire film (although let's be honest who doesn't know the tale as old as time at this point?). I'm excited to explore these characters in greater depths than the animated film got to explore, and with an over 2 hour run-time it looks like we'll be getting that and then some. The new songs look like they are going to join the ranks of some of Disney's best in their ever-growing hit catalog, and with such talent as Celine Dion and Josh Groban how can you go wrong? The actors look and sound fantastic, the film has such a colorful yet also darker ambiance to it, and the music is going to sound incredible. Words cannot describe my anticipation for this film, and I believe beyond a shadow of a doubt this will be Disney's best live-action adaptation to date!

text: Okay, so based on the teaser trailers and and photos that were previously released, I thought that this movie was going to be awful and had not sort of originality (since every single move and line seemed to come straight from the animated movie) & let's not even mention the dress... But now, it actually looks REALLY good! I like how its sticking with the original book/story (when Maurice takes a rose from the garden for Belle I think) and also with the animated movie (my favorite film of all time) with some new elements that seem like they fit in without ruining anything. The dress looks better now than before (but not as good as they made Cinderella's). I'm still a little hesitant with the CGI and Im not so sure about that Be Our Guest number but Gaston and Tale as Old as Time look amazing. I honestly cant wait now! However, I will still have my high standards.

text: Net neutrality has become an issue over the past few year that is being discussed more and more, a new law passed that will help the common people from having to overpay for the internet service. This law is called the net neutrality bill, this bill has classified the internet as a utility and therefore the internet service providers cannot charge extra to creator or consumers that use it. Net Neutrality is the principle that internet service providers should enable access to all content and application, regardless of the source, and without favoring or blocking particular products or websites. However, the internet service providers wanted to start charging to put content onto the internet and charging to access it. Bundling internet which is mandatory network sharing. I believe that unrestricted internet access, without fees and extra cost to the end user or the content creator, will help the internet keep growing and advancing into the next generation, and allow the economy to grow without restrictions with companies like Google and Amazon.  ¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† The internet is a vast computer network linking smaller networks worldwide including commercial, educational, government, and other networks, all of which use the same set of communications protocols ("The Definition of Internet."). Throughout the past 20 years the internet has boomed to take over almost every task that needs to be done. The internet holds information for people ranging from how to fix common everyday problems to how to solve some of the world‚Äôs most difficult math equations. This shows how diverse of an audience uses the internet on a regular basis. Still, the internet is still in its infancy stages because still there are many things that it can‚Äôt do for the normal consumer. All of this is still possible because the companies have left it alone for the most part letting the people decide how and what the people want to upload onto it, and what the end consumer wants to access. More recently, some of the major Internet service providers have thought about only allowing certain website run at their full potential while the rest will be throttled down to a nearly unusable speed, unless the consumer pays a premium to access the content at the normal speed. ¬†This point was covered wonderfully by the article ‚ÄúNet Neutrality and Investment Incentives‚Äù in which they said  ‚ÄúThere are two content providers who compete to deliver content to end users. Under net neutrality, the ISP cannot discriminate between content providers in the delivery speed of contents. For simplicity, let us assume that under net neutrality the ISP provides content providers with the network line at no charge. In contrast, without net neutrality regulation, preferential treatment for a particular content provider is no longer prohibited. Then, the ISP can sell the √ñrst-priority, the right to be served ahead of the other, to either one of the two content providers. As will be explained in further detail, we adopt a general framework that can capture various manners in which the √ñrst priority can be sold. In this sense, we consider access-tiring as a practice that violates network neutrality, instead of port blocking or quality degradation. ( Pil Choi)‚Äù  ¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† If The United States didn‚Äôt establish the internet as a utility the Internet Service Providers would have free control on what speeds should be set for certain people going to certain websites. These companies would have the ability to charge extra for the uploading content onto the internet. There is a great point made in ‚ÄúNet Neutrality, Unbundling, and their Effects on International Investment in Next-Generation Networks‚Äù where the author discusses how the broadband providers will have control over the quickness of one website and the slowness of another ¬†‚ÄúSo, for example, a broadband¬† provider¬† selling¬† its¬† own¬† video¬† on¬† demand¬† may¬† have¬† an¬† incentive¬† to¬† degrade¬† service quality of a company trying to sell a similar service online.( Scott W.).‚Äù With a system like this a website can create a monopoly by making sure that the other video streaming sites will be slow while theirs will be the only one to stream high quality video online. All of this is perfectly described in article written by Scott J., Wallsten, and Stephanie in which they say-  ¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄúNet neutrality debates in the U.S. have focused primarily on regulations regarding how broadband providers could price and manage traffic on their networks. The debate in Europe, and the EU in particular, has generally focused instead on the role unbundling ‚Äì mandatory network sharing ‚Äì can play in keeping networks neutral. Unbundling proponents argue that if the infrastructure provider does not offer retail services or is only one of many retailers offering service over its infrastructure it will have less incentive to discriminate in favor of or against particular content. Unbundling opponents typically do not discuss it in the context of net neutrality, but note that it can reduce incentives to invest in the underlying infrastructure (Scott p.3).‚Äù  ¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Another way the Internet Service providers will get incentives will be because they don‚Äôt have to deal with unbundling their services. While net neutrality has been discussed for many years in the United States while mandatory unbundling has barely been touched on. Most countries to all nations heavily rely on their internet service provider to give them fair and open access to watch TV and check their email on their PC by using the internet. But, when it comes to certain internet providers the only way to get it is by subscribing for a cable service as well that will go unused, which ultimately over charges the customer. The graph following this paragraph displays how over saturated the United States market is with cable compared with other countries where there is usually less than half if not less than a third of their market is for cable.  Like all things, there will be flaws that could be pointed out and this argument has some. The first being that even if America manages to unbundle there will wouldn‚Äôt necessarily be a change where incentives facing this Service Provider if the Service Provider still controls the infrastructure in which the data travels through. ¬†And the second point being that the mandatory unbundling can affect incentives to invest in the network by reducing the potential returns to that investment. Another great point made by ‚ÄúNet Neutrality, Unbundling, and their Effects on International Investment in Next-Generation Networks‚Äù is-   ‚ÄúMost countries to all nations heavily rely on their internet service provider to give them fair and open access to watch TV and check their email on their PC by using the internet. But, when it comes to certain internet providers the only way to get it is by subscribing for a cable service as well that will go unused, which ultimately over charges the customer.   All of this is clearly proven because in the UK and many other countries their internet does not have a cap on it and in Switzerland there is no bottlenecking the data speeds. It is about time that US took a stance in the right direction.  After all of this the consumer is stuck with bottlenecked (limited due to ISP) speeds on their internet. Alongside, data caps throttle the speeds way down once they are hit.‚Äù  ¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† One of the main cons concerning an internet service that runs on the back of cable, is that the bandwidth is limited to the speed of a coax cable. While Google is coming out with Google Fiber, which is a faster and over all better solution to today‚Äôs problem with internet. The problem today is that the speeds that most people get throughout the day vary a lot, which means when some the whole neighborhood sits down in the afternoon to watch some Netflix it affects everyone‚Äôs speeds throttling down everyone to low quality. With this method everyone suffers even if one person on the line is even downloading something. I have experienced this personally.

Hence when the Beast died and Belle said "I love you" it was truly a pure love.  And what we see here is that she will be aware of the curse... Apparently they are going to shatter the amazing love line from the original movie by changing important details. Let's go further, dear filmmakers, let's make the Beast and Belle say "I love you" to each other before the Beast dies (like I said, originally Belle said that only after the Beast had died, and as for the Beast, he didn't confess in love directly) to make it banal and then there will be no point in this movie at all. What a piece of ****

text: Beauty and the Beast is the tenth Disney animated film from the released 20 centuries to become a live-action remake after Dumbo, 101 Dalmatians, Alice in Wonderland, Sleeping Beauty, Cinderella, The Jungle Book, The Lion King, The Little Mermaid and Tarzan only as for a teaser of it being on The Jungle Book (2016), The Angry Birds Movie, Finding Dory and Ice Age: Collision Course! Disney animated films from the released 20 centuries to become a live-action remake and for reasons: Dumbo (Danny Glover version with the Honey, We Shrunk Ourselves trailer called "Operation: Dumbo Drop") 101 Dalmatians (for the 1996 FP logo with the 1992 WDHV logo on a Black BG from "Toy Story") Alice in Wonderland (for Johnny Depp and the Sorcerer's Apprentice trailer) Sleeping Beauty (for the 2014 movie "Maleficent" starring Angelina Jolie) Cinderella (for the 2015 movie and trailers of Minions, The Peanuts Movie, Tomorrowland, Inside Out, Hotel Transylvania 2 and Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip, where "A Dream Is A Wish Your Heart Makes" and "Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo" are the only original songs to perform) The Jungle Book (1994 with Kenny Loggins and a trailer for "A Goofy Movie" and 2016 with trailers for The Secret Life of Pets, Finding Dory, Ice Age: Collision Course, The BFG, Ratchet & Clank and Pete's Dragon, where "The Bare Necessities", "Trust in Me" and "I Wanna Be Like You" are the only original songs to perform) The Lion King (with footage from The Jungle Book (2016), The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe, The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian and The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader and the audio from the original Lion King where "Circle of Life", "I Just Can't Wait to Be King", "Hakuna Matata" and "Can You Feel the Love Tonight" are the only original songs to perform) The Little Mermaid (for the Stage Musical and the footage from Aquamarine and Disneynature's Oceans, where "Part of Your World", "Kiss the Girl" and "Under the Sea" are the only original songs to perform) Tarzan (with Warner Bros. replacing Disney) Beauty and the Beast (as for a teaser of it being on The Jungle Book (2016), The Angry Birds Movie, Finding Dory and Ice Age: Collision Course!)

text: I remember watching in a special about Disney's "Beauty and the Beast," how they had done the animated movie and then the Broadway Musical and they asked Alan Menken if they would ever do a live action movie. Alan Menken, the music composer, didn't know but knew it would be interesting and thought perhaps maybe someday. That idea remained up in the air for years. The enchanted objects would be the hard part because in an animated movie you can easily do it and with the Broadway musical, they changed the story that instead of already being objects, they were slowly turning into them and unless the spell is broken, they will eventually become... THINGS. But now that the technology exists, they knew they could take the final step and make a live action movie. I bet the late Howard Ashman, who was the executive producer and song lyricist of the animated movie would have approved of this movie. Howard Ashman and Alan Menken were an incredible song making team!

I'm giving Emma the benefit of the doubt here but, from what I've seen in the trailer, she doesn't capture the latter all that well. Like I said, I'm giving her the benefit of the doubt but Beauty And The Beast was my favorite movie growing up as a kid. text: The movie isn't out yet and people are placing their judgements already(I understand it's matter of opinion, so, here's mine). Yes, it's a remake of an iconic and beloved film which is why no matter what they do, change or keep, no one is going to be satisfied. Some people are saying Emma Watson is a terrible choice to play Belle or the movie looks exactly the same as the first film. I mean what were you all expecting? I mean could any of you have done better job with the story or even played the character Belle? We all can relate to Belle in some ways but can any of you actually play her character or write her story? Beauty and the Beast is one of my favourite childhood movies and yes, I was nervous when they announced that they were doing a remake live action but I refuse to place my judgments when I haven't seen the movie yet...

text: The Beast is a little underwhelming... the original design was so perfect and this just looks like... some average CGI via a standard¬†Star-Trek prosthetic style... there are so many amazing things that can be done with real, physical effects which¬†make everything far more "real"... think about how impressive Tim Curry was as Darkness in "Legend"...the human brain is¬†smart enough to register something as CGI and consequently "not real" which¬†kind of robs it of some impact and drama... given that he¬†is a legend and did a great job on another Disney property recently, Maleficent, why didn't¬†Rick Baker do this?¬†The original¬†Beauty and the Beast¬†animation was so brilliant and this required someone of legendary status to meet that challenge... plus, he was already very familiar with the whole Beauty and the Beast shtick from his TV series... ah well, bit of an opportunity missed... will go and see it as the musical arrangements sound reasonably good still and¬†out of love of the original...

text: When I was a child and beauty and the beast was made into a disney animation, it was then that you could only get the beauty required to fill Walt's true goal for Disney as a whole through the colors and animation. Now that it's 2017 Disney can present a magical movie filled with real actors and actresses because of how far CGI and computer's have come in general. The Cinderella movie was much more interesting and appealing as a live action film vs the classic IMO. Although these classics can not be replaced I have a feeling in generations to come these will become the staple. Simply beautiful and Ariana and John really didn't let us down. Celine and Peabo did amazing and so did this new generation of musical entertainers. Walt would be so proud of you all and  how you kept his dream intact at every turn.

text: I find it very disturbing that the Beast has horns and actually looks devilish. He is portrayed in a similar manner to Mephistopheles, a fictional yet devilish character in opera. What message is this giving to our young girls? That someone that looks that scary, that bad, is to be pursued? As a Christian, I am concerned about this movie not only scaring but indoctrinating our girl children into a culture of "bad is good." Imagine a scenario when a young girl, heaven forbid, is lured or even abducted by a child rapist/murdered. Is she going to use her instincts and try to get away, or will she remember this movie and ignore the red flags?

text: They lived in a nice safe town because Gaston defended it. He kept all of those people safe, so that they could have libraries and bakery shops and all of the things they enjoyed. He just wanted the best girl in town but she wouldn't even be polite or give him the time of day. She was kidnapped by a monster, a beast in a dark castle caused by the fact that he was a crap person when he was a human. And he was a crap person to Belle as a monster. There was no difference in the way that the Beast treated her and the way that Gaston treated her. Actually the Beast may have been worse. But he had that BBC and she wanted that beastiality. Gaston wanted to protect the people of his town, save the woman who had been held captive, win her love, and be the hero that the town adored. Instead the guy who had been a jerk his whole life and got turned into a monster as a result got the girl. What a POS love story. *Gaston did nothing wrong.*

text: As a die hard fan of the original, I have high expectations for this. When I watched it today, I have mixed feelings about this, sure it's good but for me it doesn't reach the heights of the original animated film   and I left expecting a little more. There are a lots of moments that were handled better in the original, a hell lot of them actually. It expanded the tale by adding some backstories but it doesn't improve it in any way. It lacks the warmth, majesty and magic of it's predecessors. For a two hour movie, this one felt forced and rushed. The animated classic managed to satisfy me in 85 minutes It entertains me, but it wasn't enough. To everyone who watched this, I'm sure you don't want to see it again a multiple times, instead you'll revisit the the original which is perfection.

text: I know that now you kill me. But I have to say it. I really think that Emma Watson is not good for this role in this film. She only has the same one expression on her face. I'm sorry. I really, really love. But ok. I have to say that to me she is largely overrated. She did not have the strength and the delicacy, the courage and the sweetness of the character of Belle, her intelligence, her rebellious spirit, her force as a woman who loves.¬† Ok... The director said "I don't want the princess, I want the woman, it's not a tale, it's a story". BAH! Walking with a book and¬† Watching the library with big eyes it's not enough to say that Belle is emancipated and a free and innovative spirit...i know that this actress is a kind of symbol, she is and she is represented as the actress who wants to emancipate girls with herself and what she does, trough her art... But I really think she needs to develop better her talent from the Hermione character... What I saw today is a Hermione, with a lower profile, in a yellow dress. No character's magic, no development, no intelligence, no mistery... Nothing... Only the same one expression... ¬†This film is overrated. Ok, the special effects were WOW, but the only one character who really works maybe it's Gaston (but not so much...).  What about the "plus" that the real film had to bring to this story? I see thousands of steps back. I found ridiculous that the great story, the magic, the real life, the poetry, the sense of a bright future... the real sense of this story, the angst and the courage, the sadness and the happiness, the great characters, their personalities and spirits work better IN A CARTOON than I a film with REAL PEOPLE. It's a pity.

text: I watched the movie last night *No spoilers* and I wasn't sure what to expect, but I was pleasantly surprised. We learn a bit more about Belles fathers back story, and at times the movie really gets your adrenaline pumping. There are a few new songs, one of which I was just thinking 'please end this song now!' but overall it was beautifully shot. Much less 'polished' and more 'busy' feeling. I felt the prologue was a bit rushed, and the iconic ballroom scene was a bit 'meh' but there were definitely one or two moments where my jaw dropped and i think Disney was brave to add the violence which they did. It's certainly quite dark in places, which I loved! I didn't see Hermione Granger. I saw Belle, and personally I think Emma did a great job of bringing belle to life. Stand out performances for me are Gaston, Mrs Potts and Lumiere. Hope you all enjoy! X

text: Once upon a time, in a faraway land, a young actor lived in a shining castle. But then, one winter's night, Julian Fellowes came to the castle and offered him a single rose in hopes he would return for the fourth season of Downton Abbey. The actor sneered at the gift and said he would not be returning for the fourth season. Julian Fellowes turned into a beautiful enchantress. The actor tried to apologize, but it was too late, for Julian had seen that there was no pity for the poor fans in his heart. And as punishment, Julian transformed him into a hideous beast and placed a powerful spell on the castle and all who lived there.

text: GREAT MOVIE! TERRIBLE EXPERIENCE! My mother and younger brothers went to watch Beauty and the Beast at Marcus Palace Cinema in the Big Screen Bistro. She placed an order and BEFORE even getting her food, the server asked to swipe her card. 40 minutes into the movie and still no food while the other guests are being served. She continued to press the service button until finally, a male server came by. He completely IGNORED her when she asked if her order was placed and by the end of the movie, STILL NO FOOD. The same server who took her original order came by and said she would get a manager but NEVER CAME BACK. By the end of the credits, still NO ONE. and NO MANAGER. She exits the Bistro with my brothers and asks a staff member for a manager because she was charged but didn't receive her order. He asked if her server was AFRICAN AMERICAN. (Her server was NOT African American. And why does the server's RACE MATTER?) He tells her he's busy and can't get her a manager then turns away. She repeats herself and FINALLY he goes to get one but NEVER RETURNS. She goes to find a DIFFERENT staff member who asks the SAME QUESTION. "WAS YOUR SERVER AFRICAN AMERICAN?" And he goes to find the server that took her order but NEVER COMES BACK EITHER. Then FINALLY the manager comes. All the manager says is, "We are very busy and have over 500 people to serve." WAS SHE NOT ONE OF YOUR GUESTS TO SERVE??? And when my mom asked why her card was swiped in the beginning, the manager says "we swipe cards for people who might eat and LEAVE." (We are asian by the way) Did my mother LOOK LIKE THE TYPE WHO WASN'T GOING TO PAY? BASED ON RACE??? I am appalled and disgusted by the way my MOTHER WAS TREATED!!! AND WITH MY YOUNGER BROTHERS AS WELL! RACIST, RUDE, IGNORANT STAFF AND MANAGEMENT!

text: This just scored 70% on rotten tomatoes which I'm not surprised about. In fact the only adaptation from cartoon to real life actors that has scored any critical acclaim worth noting is the jungle book. That, my friends, is a surprise. When will Disney learn that the magic these films are comprised of lie within the animation itself? It is a part of the creative beauty. Converting the roles to Hollywood actors is lost in CGI effects and an inability to create the wander and majesty these films deliver in their original context. I think this is a wonderful adaptation of the original film but, ten years from now, every amazing Disney film that we grew up watching and loving will be converted to this realistic nonsense, at risk of poor casting choice or acting errors. Some of these dogs must be left to lie where they are.

She didn't just stay in the palace down below like her father said, she went out and did her own thing and followed her dreams. Hey you know what I liked about Pocahontas? She didn't just do was was expected of her, she reached out and beyond the boundry and did her own thing. Hey you know what I liked about Mulan? She didn't just stay a meek bride like was expected of her, she really had her own opinions and did her own thing, Hey you know what I liked about Rapunzel? ETC ETC ETC. Bell is not special and ALL the Disney princesses are written this way.

text: I thought everything about the movie was quite good.  Spent about half of it holding back tears because I kept remembering my daughter, at that time about 7 years old, watching the original film with me.  She has a great voice and knows every single lyric.  Finally lost it during the big love-song dance.  The beginning scene was utterly remarkable, as was the ending.  Still, there are a couple of things that bothered me.  First, the one character that wasn't "fleshed" out for me enough was Belle.  Emma Watson seemed to spend half the movie attempting to get into the role, really feel it as the other character actors were doing, but never quite got there.  I can't help but feel there were any number of female actors that might have pulled it off better.  The Beast couldn't be improved on.  Gaston's character about stole the show; very well thought out and as much quality time in the film as Belle's character.  Tons of meat in the entire portrayal.  Put another way, compare Gaston to Belle and it seems the movie revolved around him; which isn't what anyone would expect.  There were a couple of scenes in the movie that went on and on and on, but weren't anything about Beauty or the Beast.  If a poll had been taken of everyone coming out of the screening of the movie, think everyone would agree that the movie didn't need changes, just simply another 20 minutes of real quality time and budding love between the two main characters.  I wonder if Emma's laid-back style of acting was somehow affecting what the producers did.

text: This movie was a masterpiece. It brought one of my favorite fairy tales to life. Emma fit the part both appearance and personality wise, even her singing was good (credit to Paige O'Hara for training her ü§ó). The whole cast was fantastic but I really liked Gaston, Beast, and Mrs. Pott's performances. It really bugs me to see so many comments saying "did I just see the whole movie?" and "it's all CGI blehhh." 1, this is a live action REMAKE of the original film, which is very popular therefore most people who have or are going to see this have probably seen the original film. This means you ALREADY KNOW THE STORY, so why do you care so much if it was a little too revealing in the trailer? Even if you haven't, don't think of this as spoilers, but as a tribute. Beauty and the Beast is one of my favorite Disney movies ever, and this adaptation really did it justice. If you haven't seen the movie then you should know better than to click on the trailer because a LOT of trailers reveal too much these days (which for the record I hate too but with cases like these I'm okay with it because I already know the story.) 2, who cares??? Most movies use CGI these days. While I agree that sometimes they use it where it isn't necessary (*cough Jurassic World *cough) I think this movie had every right to use CGI. What did you think they were going to do? Find an actual talking candlestick and teach it to sing and dance? People like this need to stop being so hard to please because whether they use CGI or not you'll never be satisfied. When they do they're like, "Ew it's CGI it looks so fake" and when they don't they say it looks cheesy or find some other way to bash the film. Do you have any idea how hard the people who made this movie worked? I make movies myself and I can say that it takes me five to six MONTHS just to make a simple five minute stop motion let alone a 2 hour adaptation of a classic that could never be replaced. The pressure to make this rememberable was probably very high, and not just for the editors. The actors must have felt pretty pressured, too, to deliver a good performance, especially Emma since her most recognizable role is Hermione. She and everyone else did their best to make this the best live action remake, so for those people who like to criticize Disney and everyone in the movie business these days, how about you pull that stick out of your butt and leave the comment section? Thank you. (sorry I just had to rant üòÇ).

text: Beauty and the Beast is by far one of my most favourite movies.  The story it portrays, the music and magic and morals knowing that love heals all, unfortunately, I only saw and felt all that from the animated version and not this one. This movie lacked the good old "warm and fuzzy" feeling you get from Disney's animated movies, it lacked "heart." It just seemed a little emotionless and forced, some bits even seem rushed, other parts had nothing to do with the original at all. I was looking forward to see how Beast would be as a "realistic" version but they didn't capture Beast's imagery or  personality at all and I feel the same way about Emma Watson playing "Belle" I like Emma Watson, she is a great actress but she is no "Belle." I wanted to like this movie and I was hoping for the same satisfaction as I got from the animation, but I couldn't. I have been a Disney fan all my life but I think Disney should have left this one alone, sorry but the animation was better.

text: this is a awesome movie. disney has done it again. they turned one of their animated movies live and did a awesome job at it. i have been waiting a long time for them to make this movie and i was not disappointed. this movie lives up to the original animated film. and i was excited to see that the ballroom scene and the musical number of be our guest was dead on to the original movie and not changed in lyrics or the scene whatsoever. and i was surprised that they put in a lot of other musical numbers in the film from the original and none of them were changed either. there was not to many changes in the film and for what was changed or added fit the movie it kept true to the original. the cast is amazing. emma watson is belle as soon as you hear her sing for the first time it blew my mind away i did not know she could sing and she is belle the same goes for everyone else they portrayed the characters so well. they could of not picked a better cast. disney is known for this. the special effects are amazing and i like how they make you feel that the servants used to be people and the transition of beast being an arrogant asshole to the good guy he becomes in the end. and i like how they added his past and belles. great movie glad it was finally made. if you have not seen this movie then i recommend you do and the music is amazing as well rating 5/5

text: I can't and will never even watch this ever again. This was a movie i took my ex girlfriend to see right after it hit the theaters. A movie she was dying to see and of course i took care of her and we went to see it. She broke up with me on May 14th. You know when you love somebody so much that when they leave you for whatever reason, you feel like your hearts been ripped out (literally a hole in your chest), thrown onto the ground and stepped on? Yeah, regardless of the fact that we'd only been dating for 4 months. We had absolutely become glued to each other. Now she's gone from my life for the time being. Watching this literally hurts inside, in fact i still have the movie tickets from when we went. She thought we should break up because she had just been accepted to an accelerated nursing program at a university and after a week she realized her unbearable work load was too much and she works and baby sits part time. So she said she would have no time for a relationship (me). While i am happy she got into the program and she is pursuing her dream. I never thought nor wanted it to result in the end of our relationship. I've actually implemented the usual no contact rule of course. I'm waiting for her to miss me and text me to see how i am doing, if not then it's her loss. Basically i will never be able to buy this movie because i will be reopening this deep wound that i am trying to heal. It's a shame too, she and i really enjoyed it too. Such a shame how we give so much of ourselves to others only for our love and compassion to become worth nothing in the end. Like watering and nurturing a flower and feeling happy for the progress you're making, only for it suddenly die.

text: Film fans will happily accept completely artificial animation like the beautiful drawings from the cartoon features Disney that were made when the master was still alive. And, of course, nobody blinks an eye at films photographed with real humans in convincing settings. But mix the two together and you have a problem. It's called the "Uncanny Valley" and the new Beauty and the Beast falls right into that classic sinkhole.  The problem of the "Uncanny Valley " became famous among animated films when Polar Express was released. A hyper-realistic Tom Hanks starred as the train conductor, his movements and even his facial expressions reproduced as computer animation through motion capture. It was the nadir of the "Uncanny Valley". Between artistic renderings and the filming of real actors, computer animated film visuals become "creepy" and even "repulsive" as they become more and more realistic. It's a bit like watching a greeting from a robot with a perfectly rendered plastic human face...fascinating but oddly scary. That's what happened with the supposedly reassuring depiction of Tom Hanks as the train conductor in Polar Express. The computerized animation was too realistic, yet false and so fell into that uncomfortable valley between artwork and photography. Beauty and the Beast tumbles deep into the Uncanny Valley by inserting real-life faces, mostly of Emma Watson, into entirely animatronic settings, impossible costumes and among jarringly artificial characters' faces.  Once again, this "heartwarming" animated remake fails to transport the audience anywhere but the dreaded valley where reality and artifice collide.  Perhaps kids who aren't jaded by an excess of film technology will be carried away, but there's no masking the weirdness of the newest $150 million Disney cartoon/reality creation.
author: George Wolff

text: I know that many people criticize live action ballroom being emotionless, and I agree, but then again it was such a strong pressure on Emma & Dan, & Disney itself, to overpower their most emotional and iconic dance to date. Of course its easier to draw anything you want than to portray in real life, that's why you see more emotion here. Emma was mostly all alone talking to green screens or boring robots during filming (cgi was really OVER USED in be our guest), if they at least made Dan wear a real Beast costume, maybe just for ballroom scene, it would be more real and filled with romance like this one. I like both versions, some scenes I prefer animated some live, but ballroom from animated will always be my favorite Disney scene in general. And yes, this is the best remake ;)

text: Emma was really the worst part of the movie (together with too much CGI during Be Our Guest), but I think it wasn't all her fault. She just wasn't Belle for this adaption. Maybe a Belle in a modern setting, similar to Vanesa Hudgens in Beastly, for this one they should really look for another actress. Designers did great job, but also failed - Belle didn't wear fallen shoulders dress, neither her iconic gloves - the ballroom scene also lacks emotion, they could make Dan wear the Beast costume just for that scene. Beast actually does look great, they based him on his looks of the original tale, where he has that appearance - an elegant goat (not a powerful bull-lion-werewolf like in animated). Gaston & enchanted furniture were amazing in every way.

text: I completely Forgot about this New Adaptation of one of my old classic fables of Beauty & The Beast as 2017 was brimming over with Triple A Blockbusters released in the same year & after reading a brief on how well it did at the Box Office I figured it was time to finally have a quick look at the trailer & by all accounts from the very brief section I looked at I can see why it was a Box Office Hit... As it looks like they've (for what I can see in this trailer) taken the classic Disney Animated version & updated it with today's state of the art CGI graphics/large sets/great costumes & actors who look like they wanted to do this fable justice via their acting capabilities...  I've seen many versions of Beauty & The Beast from Disney's Animated Musical Classic to versions that didn't use the name but were definitely taking direct cues from the subject matter of this films...  It looks as if they've created the animated version into a CGI film along with a cast of actors & added the songs also, though I'm not sure if the theme song was just used for the trailer & if there are all the songs from the animated version...  I actually remember the enjoyable late 80's Tv series of Beauty & The Beast which was set in moden times with Linda Hamilton of Terminator/Terminator 2  & the New Rebooted Version of Terminator out soon who played Catherine Chandler... Along with versatile character actor Ron Perlman playing Vincent & this was long before the many movies he has been before this Tv Series & long after...  And of course the film that made him a worldwide name which was Guillermo Del Toro's beautiful looking take on Hellboy & Hellboy 2 The Golden Army...  I found the updated Tv Series version set in a modern environment to be handled with taste & storylines that earned it much praise & awards...  Looks like I missed a little gem here which I'll need to add to my to watch list...  .....
